Re: Quick Translation - Grammatical Error?
by NileCat » Mon 08.17.2009 12:38 am You are not wrong. Both are fine.But, well... generally speaking, when the term is shown alone like you did here.一番仲のいい友達 would be preferable as a " good Japanese ". But among young people, some of them would prefer the latter.Well, and I know it is not necessarily true, but 一番仲のいい友達 sounds more matured.EDITED
Last edited by NileCat on Mon 08.17.2009 10:58 am, edited 1 time in total.
NileCat
